The Telegraph - Calcutta : Metro

 The City Diary

 Bids were opened on Friday for the handover of Railway Yatri Niwas at Howrah station, now run by Indian Railway Catering and Tourism Corporation (IRCTC). Officials said Benfish and Chennai-based American Enterprises and a Visakhapatnam-based firm are in the race for the takeover of Yatri Niwas on a 15-year lease. The new management will run it on a redevelopment-operation-management-transfer basis. Bids for handover of BNR hotels in Puri and Ranchi and Railway Yatri Niwas of New Delhi, too, were opened on Friday.

 Pradip Das, 26, and Asish Chatterjee, 34, were arrested on Friday on charges of taking away the motorcycle of advocate Kaushik Kundu in Beleghata on November 15 night. Deputy commissioner of the detective department Gyanwant Singh said the armed duo stopped Kundu near Alochhaya cinema while he was returning home.

 The investiture and bravery awards ceremony of Calcutta Police will be held on Monday at the Calcutta Police auditorium in Alipore. Chief minister Buddhadeb Bhattacharjee will be the chief guest.

 Chief minister Buddhadeb Bhattacharjee will inaugurate the five-day Industrial Trade Fair at Circus Ground at Sinthee More on Saturday. The fair will showcase products from North 24-Parganas and its adjacent places. Finance minister Asim Dasgupta said on Friday that the government is organising the fair as a pilot project to provide a platform for entrepreneurs.

 Health minister Surjya Kanta Mishra on Thursday inaugurated the Master of Hospital Administration course at Peerless Hospital and B.K.Roy Research Centre. The course is affiliated to West Bengal University of Technology.

 The data collection programme of Census 2006, the market research initiative of Indian Institute of Management Calcutta, is scheduled for December 30 and 31 at 22 Camac Street.

